				<p><p>There are couple of ways to detect road surface. One is to use planar gradients (like linear gradients in 3D) as mentioned in @ArminMeisterhirn 's answer. (<a href="http://www.pointclouds.org/assets/uploads/3DRP-PCL14_Bellone.pdf" rel="nofollow noreferrer">http://www.pointclouds.org/assets/uploads/3DRP-PCL14_Bellone.pdf</a>)</p>

<p>Other one is to use associative learning; We can identify objects in image (like cars, roads etc some hints can be found in this video <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j8zj5lBpFTY" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j8zj5lBpFTY</a> ) and use corresponding point cloud data and train the second stage with corresponding 3D objects. (Like using CNN for object classification/ training as per <a href="http://www.image-net.org/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">ImageNet</a>) (Example attempt: <a href="https://people.csail.mit.edu/fisher/publications/papers/mastin09cvpr.pdf" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://people.csail.mit.edu/fisher/publications/papers/mastin09cvpr.pdf</a>)</p>

<p>I prefer second option and usage of AI. There is a database containing both images and other sensors' data timestamped by software automatically as available <a href="http://grandchallenge.mit.edu/wiki/index.php?title=PublicData" rel="nofollow noreferrer">http://grandchallenge.mit.edu/wiki/index.php?title=PublicData</a> . </p>
